# shadcn instructions

Use the latest version of Shadcn to install new components, like this command to add a button component:

```bash
pnpm dlx shadcn@latest add button
```

# Project Agent Guide

> This document is the source of truth for any AI agent or developer working on this codebase. Read it fully before making changes.

---

## Stack

- **Framework:** TanStack Start (file-based routing via `src/routes/`)
- **Database ORM:** Drizzle ORM
- **Language:** TypeScript (strict mode вЂ” no `any`, no implicit types)
- **Architecture:** Feature-based (see below)

---

## Project Structure

```
src/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ db/
в”‚   в”њв”Ђв”Ђ index.ts              # Drizzle client instance
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ schemas/
в”‚       в”њв”Ђв”Ђ index.ts          # Re-exports all schemas
в”‚       в””в”Ђв”Ђ *.ts              # One file per domain entity
в”‚
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ features/
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ [feature-name]/
в”‚       в”њв”Ђв”Ђ index.ts          # Public API вЂ” only export what consumers need
в”‚       в”њв”Ђв”Ђ [feature].schema.ts   # Zod schemas & inferred types
в”‚       в”њв”Ђв”Ђ [feature].queries.ts  # DB read functions (SELECT)
в”‚       в”њв”Ђв”Ђ [feature].mutations.ts # DB write functions (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE)
в”‚       в”њв”Ђв”Ђ [feature].service.ts  # Business logic, orchestration
в”‚       в”њв”Ђв”Ђ [feature].hooks.ts    # React hooks (client-side)
в”‚       в”њв”Ђв”Ђ components/           # UI components scoped to this feature
в”‚       в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ *.tsx
в”‚       в””в”Ђв”Ђ __tests__/
в”‚           в”њв”Ђв”Ђ [feature].queries.test.ts
в”‚           в”њв”Ђв”Ђ [feature].mutations.test.ts
в”‚           в””в”Ђв”Ђ [feature].service.test.ts
в”‚
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ routes/
в”‚   в””в”Ђв”Ђ **                    # TanStack Start file-based routes
в”‚
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ components/               # Truly shared, cross-feature UI components only
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ lib/                      # Shared utilities (formatters, helpers, constants)
в””в”Ђв”Ђ types/                    # Global TypeScript types and interfaces
```

---

## Feature Module Rules

### 1. Every feature is self-contained

A feature owns its own data access, business logic, validation, and UI. It should not directly import internals from another feature. If two features need to share logic, extract it to `src/lib/`.

### 2. Each file in a feature has one job

| File | Responsibility |
|---|---|
| `[feature].schema.ts` | Zod validation schemas + inferred TypeScript types |
| `[feature].queries.ts` | Read-only DB functions. Import Drizzle client from `src/db` |
| `[feature].mutations.ts` | Write DB functions (create, update, delete) |
| `[feature].service.ts` | Orchestrates queries/mutations + business rules. No raw DB calls here |
| `[feature].hooks.ts` | React hooks wrapping service calls for client components |
| `index.ts` | Public API. Only re-export what route files or other features should use |

### 3. Public API via `index.ts`

Never import from a feature's internal files directly. Always go through its `index.ts`.

```ts
// вњ… Correct
import { getUserById } from "@/features/users";

// вќЊ Wrong
import { getUserById } from "@/features/users/users.queries";
```

### 4. Drizzle usage

- Import the db client from `@/db` (maps to `src/db/index.ts`)
- Import schemas from `@/db/schemas` (maps to `src/db/schemas/index.ts`)
- Keep raw Drizzle calls inside `*.queries.ts` and `*.mutations.ts` only
- Never write raw DB calls in services, hooks, or route files

```ts
// src/features/users/users.queries.ts
import { db } from "@/db";
import { users } from "@/db/schemas";
import { eq } from "drizzle-orm";

export async function getUserById(id: string) {
  return db.query.users.findFirst({
    where: eq(users.id, id),
  });
}
```

### 5. Validation with Zod

All input validation lives in `[feature].schema.ts`. Infer TypeScript types from schemas вЂ” don't write them manually.

```ts
// src/features/users/users.schema.ts
import { z } from "zod";

export const createUserSchema = z.object({
  name: z.string().min(1),
  email: z.string().email(),
});

export type CreateUserInput = z.infer<typeof createUserSchema>;
```

### 6. Services orchestrate, they don't persist

Services call queries and mutations. They apply business rules, compose multiple operations, throw typed errors. They never call `db` directly.

```ts
// src/features/users/users.service.ts
import { createUserSchema, type CreateUserInput } from "./users.schema";
import { getUserByEmail } from "./users.queries";
import { insertUser } from "./users.mutations";

export async function createUser(input: CreateUserInput) {
  const parsed = createUserSchema.parse(input); // always validate at boundary

  const existing = await getUserByEmail(parsed.email);
  if (existing) throw new Error("Email already in use");

  return insertUser(parsed);
}
```

---

## Testing

### Philosophy

- Every `*.queries.ts`, `*.mutations.ts`, and `*.service.ts` file should have a corresponding test file in `__tests__/`
- Tests are written to be deterministic and fast вЂ” mock the DB in unit tests
- Integration tests (hitting a real test DB) go in a separate `*.integration.test.ts` file

### Test file naming convention

```
__tests__/
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ users.queries.test.ts       # Unit tests вЂ” mock db
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ users.mutations.test.ts     # Unit tests вЂ” mock db
в”њв”Ђв”Ђ users.service.test.ts       # Unit tests вЂ” mock queries/mutations
в””в”Ђв”Ђ users.service.integration.test.ts  # Optional: real DB calls
```

### What to test

- **Queries/Mutations:** Test the shape of returned data and that the correct Drizzle methods are called with the right arguments
- **Services:** Test business logic branches (happy path, validation failure, conflict cases)
- **Hooks:** Test using React Testing Library if they have meaningful logic
- **Components:** Test critical user interactions, not implementation details

---

## Code Quality Rules

These apply everywhere, always:

1. **No `any`** вЂ” use `unknown` and narrow it, or define a proper type
2. **No implicit returns** вЂ” always be explicit about what a function returns
3. **Explicit error handling** вЂ” don't silently swallow errors; log or rethrow with context
4. **Prefer `const`** over `let`; never use `var`
5. **Pure functions where possible** вЂ” easier to test, easier to reason about
6. **Early returns** to reduce nesting (avoid deep if/else chains)
7. **Named exports only** вЂ” avoid default exports (they hurt refactoring and autocomplete)
8. **One concern per file** вЂ” if a file is doing two things, split it

---

## Adding a New Feature (Checklist)

When adding a new feature, create the following files (skip any that aren't needed yet, but don't skip tests):

- [ ] `src/features/[name]/[name].schema.ts`
- [ ] `src/features/[name]/[name].queries.ts`
- [ ] `src/features/[name]/[name].mutations.ts`
- [ ] `src/features/[name]/[name].service.ts`
- [ ] `src/features/[name]/[name].hooks.ts` *(if client-side state needed)*
- [ ] `src/features/[name]/components/` *(if UI needed)*
- [ ] `src/features/[name]/__tests__/[name].queries.test.ts`
- [ ] `src/features/[name]/__tests__/[name].mutations.test.ts`
- [ ] `src/features/[name]/__tests__/[name].service.test.ts`
- [ ] `src/features/[name]/index.ts` *(public API вЂ” export last, after everything else works)*

If you're adding a DB table for this feature, also add:
- [ ] `src/db/schemas/[name].ts`
- [ ] Export it from `src/db/schemas/index.ts`
- [ ] Generate and run the migration

---

## Adding a New DB Schema

1. Create `src/db/schemas/[entity].ts`
2. Define the table using Drizzle's schema builder
3. Export it from `src/db/schemas/index.ts`
4. Run `drizzle-kit generate` to create the migration
5. Run `drizzle-kit migrate` to apply it

---

## What Agents Should NOT Do

- Do not write business logic in route files вЂ” routes call services, nothing more
- Do not import across features except through `index.ts`
- Do not put raw SQL or Drizzle calls in service files
- Do not create global state unless absolutely necessary вЂ” keep state local to features
- Do not skip writing tests when adding queries, mutations, or service logic
- Do not leave `TODO` comments without a note on what's blocking them
